Veronika is a beautiful girl with a good job, a loving family and a boyfriend but still thereâ€™s something missing. She felt caught and oppressed by the things which should have acquired joy in her life. The void inside her develops until she settles on a definite decision a few of us have covertly murmured to ourselves then dismissed out of sheer fear. Veronika decides to die, but she didnâ€™t succeed. 
Somehow the doctors saved her and she awakened inside a mental institution but with the sad news that her heart is harmed so severally; she has just a week to live. She is presently looked with the possibility of 'waiting' for death. As the days passed, Veronika begins seeing life in a different light.
Over the course of a week Veronika began to realize that her survival instincts have started to grab hold. One of the most fascinating parts about the book is that it is told from various points of view: Veronika Deklava, Dr. Igor, and significantly different patients in the mental hospital. If for nothing else, one must give Coehlo appreciation for perfectly combining as all these distinctive, perceptive characters in to a same book. 
This was the first Coelho book I read. To start a story with a suicide attempt is a sure-fire way for picking up your readerâ€™s consideration. But it is Veronikaâ€™s progress as a lost young woman trying to find her position in the world that drew my attention. Coelhoâ€™s efforts to document these psychological transitions are admirable. 
This is a book I would recommend to any individual who has ever thought of suicide. Coelho brings up in his novel that change in perspective, regardless of how slight or sensational, can tie a falling individual more tightly to the string of life.

